# Stop Collecting Course Completion Certificates Like Trophies

## Introduction

One of the most common mistakes I see among cybersecurity beginners is the belief that collecting dozens of course completion certificates will automatically lead to a job opportunity.

Many learners spend months earning 30, 40, or even 50 certificates and assume that a large collection of certificates will impress recruiters.

Unfortunately, that is not how the cybersecurity industry works.

The industry values practical skills, hands-on experience, problem-solving ability, and real-world knowledge far more than the number of course completion certificates on a resume.

---

## Understanding the Difference

### Course Completion Certificates

A course completion certificate generally proves that a learner has completed a training program or watched educational content.

While these courses are excellent for learning new concepts, they do not necessarily demonstrate practical competency.

Examples include:

- Online learning platforms
- Video-based training courses
- Vendor training programs
- Free cybersecurity learning resources

These certificates support learning, but they should not be viewed as proof of professional capability.

---

### Industry-Recognized Certifications

Industry-recognized certifications are different because they require candidates to demonstrate knowledge, practical skills, or pass rigorous examinations.

Examples include certifications offered by:

- OffSec
- EC-Council
- TCM Security
- INE Security
- Security Blue Team
- CompTIA
- GIAC

These certifications are generally more respected by employers because they provide a stronger indication of competency.

---

## What Employers Actually Look For

Most cybersecurity hiring managers are interested in:

- Practical skills
- Home lab experience
- Security projects
- Capture The Flag (CTF) participation
- Technical documentation and write-ups
- Incident response experience
- Industry-recognized certifications

These factors help demonstrate that a candidate can apply knowledge in real-world scenarios.

---

## Quality Over Quantity

Instead of collecting dozens of course certificates, consider investing your time in:

- Building a home lab
- Practicing on TryHackMe and Hack The Box
- Creating cybersecurity projects
- Writing technical blogs
- Learning scripting and automation
- Preparing for respected certifications

A few strong projects combined with practical skills will often provide more value than a large collection of course completion certificates.

---

## Conclusion

Course completion certificates are not useless.

They are valuable learning tools and can help build foundational knowledge.

However, learners should avoid focusing solely on collecting certificates.

The goal should always be to develop practical skills and gain experience that can be demonstrated in real-world environments.

> The goal is not to collect certificates.
>
> The goal is to build skills that certificates can validate.


